            <fr:title text="Closed immersions are affine admissible">Closed immersions are affine admissible</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Proposition</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter><html:p>
  The class of <fr:link href="/schm-FH0V/" title="Closed immersion" uri="https://charloced.github.io/schm-FH0V/" display-uri="schm-FH0V" type="local">closed immersions</fr:link> are <fr:link href="/schm-NAP1/" title="Affine admissible classes" uri="https://charloced.github.io/schm-NAP1/" display-uri="schm-NAP1" type="local">affine admissible</fr:link>.
</html:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors /><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>6</fr:month><fr:day>17</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
  <html:p>
    Closed immersions are evidently closed under compositions. For pullbacks, it suffices to observe that they are <fr:link href="/schm-WURZ/" title="Affine local on the target" uri="https://charloced.github.io/schm-WURZ/" display-uri="schm-WURZ" type="local">affine local</fr:link> and closed immersions of affine schemes, which corresponds to quotients of the form <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D \twoheadrightarrow  I/D]]></fr:tex> for some ideal <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D]]></fr:tex>, are closed under pushouts.
  </html:p>
  <html:p>
    Now to show it is affine local, suppose we have a morphism of schemes <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[C \to  X]]></fr:tex> where for an affine open cover <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X = \bigcup _{i}\operatorname {Spec} A_i]]></fr:tex>, the restriction <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[C_i \to  \operatorname {Spec} A_i]]></fr:tex> is a closed immersion. Then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[C]]></fr:tex> must be closed in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>, and the ideal sheaf corresponding to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[C]]></fr:tex> must be quasi-coherent, since they are quasi-coherent on each affine open. Hence, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[C \to  X]]></fr:tex> is a closed immersion.
  </html:p>
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
</fr:mainmatter>
